.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion

.SH AUTHORS
Jana Rasheed Bakri
.br
Badr Abdulaziz Almutairi

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string and a variable number of arguments.
Output is written to the standard output stream (stdout) using the
.B write(2)
system call.

The
.I format
string is composed of zero or more characters and conversion
specifiers. Ordinary characters are printed as-is.

A conversion specifier starts with the character '%' and is followed by
a character indicating how the argument should be formatted.

For this project,
.B _printf()
implements a subset of the functionality of the C standard library
printf(3).

.SS Supported conversion specifiers
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string. If the argument is NULL, the string
"(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

Unsupported conversion specifiers are printed as-is (the '%' and the
following character).

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the terminating
null byte).

If an error occurs (such as a NULL format string), the function returns
-1.

.SH ERRORS
.TP
.B EINVAL
Returned when the format string is NULL.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print simple text:
.PP
.nf
    _printf("Hello, Holberton!\\n");
.fi

Print formatted data:
.PP
.nf
    int n = 42;
    _printf("Value: %d\\n", n);
.fi

Print characters and strings:
.PP
.nf
    _printf("Letter: %c, Word: %s\\n", 'A', "School");
.fi

Print a percent sign:
.PP
.nf
    _printf("100%% complete\\n");
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3)

